<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="../../w/index-title=Standard_language&action=edit&section=1.php.html" title="Edit section: Characteristics">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Characteristics">Characteristics</span></h2>
<p>The only requirement for a variety to be standard is that it can frequently be used in public places or public discourse.<sup id="cite_ref-fineganp14_1-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-fineganp14-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> The creation of a <a href="Prescription_and_description" title="Prescription and description" class="mw-redirect">prescriptive</a> standard language derives from a desire for <a href="Nationalism" title="Nationalism">national</a> (<a href="Cultural_uniformity" title="Cultural uniformity" class="mw-redirect">cultural</a>, political, and <a href="Social_cohesion" title="Social cohesion">social</a>) cohesion with this considered as requiring an agreed-upon, standardized language variety.<sup class="Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="Wikipedia_Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources from October 2011">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> Standard languages commonly feature:</p>
<ul>
<li>A recognized <a href="Dictionary" title="Dictionary">dictionary</a> (standardized <a href="Spelling" title="Spelling">spelling</a> and <a href="Vocabulary" title="Vocabulary">vocabulary</a>)</li>
<li>A recognized <a href="Grammar" title="Grammar">grammar</a></li>
<li>A standard <a href="Pronunciation" title="Pronunciation">pronunciation</a> (educated speech)</li>
<li>A linguistic institution defining usage norms, e.g. <a href="Acad%C3%A9mie_fran%C3%A7aise" title="Académie française">Académie française</a>, or <a href="Royal_Spanish_Academy" title="Royal Spanish Academy" class="mw-redirect">Real Academia Española</a></li>
<li>Constitutional (<a href="Law" title="Law">legal</a>) status (frequently as an <a href="Official_language" title="Official language">official language</a>)</li>
<li>Effective public use (court, legislature, schools)</li>
<li>A <a href="Literature" title="Literature">literary</a> <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/canon" class="extiw" title="wikt:canon">canon</a></li>
<li>Convenience speaking<sup id="cite_ref-VahidR_4-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-VahidR-4"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Popularity and acceptance in the community<sup id="cite_ref-VahidR_4-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-VahidR-4"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Population<sup id="cite_ref-VahidR_4-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-VahidR-4"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup></li>
</ul>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="../../w/index-title=Standard_language&action=edit&section=2.php.html" title="Edit section: List of standard languages and regulators">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="List_of_standard_languages_and_regulators">List of standard languages and regulators</span></h2>
